to their court. Under the rule of Nasr ibn Ahmad II (r. 914-943), Rudaki distinguished himself as the brightest literary star of the Samanid court.This book presents Rudaki as the founder of a new poetic aesthetic, which was adopted by subsequent generations of Persian poets. Rudaki is credited with being the first to write in the rubâi form; and many of the images we first encounter in Rudaki's lines have become staples of Persian poetry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 4aCultural Studies. 4aLIT. 4aLanguage and Literature. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aMiddle East. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Persian.2bisacsh  aClassical Persian Literature, Persian Poetry, Rudaki.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311102378640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789400600164zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789400600164zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789400600164/original  a978-3-11-102378-6 Amsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA